HW5 Problem 1

a. Plot and interpret the posteriors for p assuming a beta prior with parameters (2, 2), (1, 1) and (.5, .5).

  • Assume that data is (one) observation from random variable \(X \sim Binom(n, p)\), where \(p\) probability of success (here: egg exploding). Observed data: \(n=20\), \(x=17\).

  • Prior. Prior distribution is a distribution that is supposed to reflect what we know about \(p\) prior to seeing the data. We assume the prior distribution is \(p \sim Beta(\alpha, \beta)\) and is given by probability density function \[ f(p) = f(p|\alpha, \beta) = \frac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha) \Gamma(\beta)} p^{\alpha - 1} (1-p)^{\beta -1}. \] In that sense, we consider \(p\) to be continuous random variable.

  • Likelihood. Here, likelihood for \(p\) (function of the parameter given the data) is given by probability mass function \[ L(p):=\operatorname{Pr}(x \mid p) = \binom{n}{x}p^x (1-p)^{n-x} \]

  • Posterior distribution. It can be derived from Bayes Theorem that combining the prior distribution and the likelihood gives us \[ f(p \mid x) \propto \operatorname{Pr}(x \mid p) f(p) \] where \(\propto\) means proportional to. Here, the \(f(q \mid x)\) will be probability density function because we consider \(p\) to be continuous random variable. \[ \begin{align*} f(p \mid x) &= f(p|\alpha, \beta; x) = \text{Prior} \times \text{Likelihood} \\ &= f(p|\alpha, \beta) \cdot f(x|p)\\ &= \frac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha) \Gamma(\beta)} p^{\alpha - 1} (1-p)^{\beta -1} \cdot \binom{n}{x}p^x (1-p)^{n-x} \\ & \propto p^{\alpha + x - 1} (1-p)^{(n-x) + \beta - 1} \\ & = p^{\alpha^{*} - 1} (1-p)^{\beta^{*} - 1} \end{align*} \] where \(\alpha^{*} = \alpha + x\), \(\beta^{*} = (n-x) + \beta\).

  • To tell what distribution \(f(q \mid x)\) represents, we look at the \(f(q \mid x)\) formula we got and recognize it being PDF of some distribution we know. Here, we see the last line is close to density of \(Beta(\alpha^{*}, \beta^{*})\) distribution up to a scalar (here, scalar := expression free from parameter \(p\)): \[ \frac{\Gamma(\alpha^{*} + \beta^{*})}{\Gamma(\alpha^{*}) \Gamma(\beta^{*})} p^{\alpha^{*} - 1} (1-p)^{\beta^{*} -1} = \text{scalar} \cdot p^{\alpha^{*} - 1} (1-p)^{\beta^{*} -1} \] hence we conclude the posterior distribution of \(p\) is \(Beta(\alpha^{*}, \beta^{*})\) = \(Beta(\alpha + x, (n-x) + \beta)\).

  • Note the posterior distribution combines infromation from both:

    • prior distribution, as it uses so-called hyperparameters \(\alpha\), \(\beta\),
    • data (likelihood), as it uses \(x\) and \(n\).
n <- 20
x <- 17
p <- seq(0, 1, length = 1000)

# Calculate priors and posterior
beta.params <- list(c(2, 2), c(1, 1), c(0.5, 0.5))
priors <- lapply(beta.params, function(param, p) 
  dbeta(p, param[1], param[2]), p = p)
posteriors <- lapply(beta.params, function(param, p) 
  dbeta(p, param[1]+ x, n - x + param[2]), p = p)

# Translate into df and plot
data.frame(p = rep(p, 3), param = rep(c(2, 1, 0.5), each = 1000), 
           prior = unlist(priors), posterior = unlist(posteriors)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = p, color = factor(param))) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 17/20) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = prior), linetype = 2) +
  geom_line(aes(y = posterior)) + 
  labs(title = "Prior (dashed) and Posterior (solid) Beta Distributions\nGrey line: sample proportion x/n=17/20", 
       x = "p", y = "PDF", color = TeX('$\\alpha = \\beta$')) + 
  theme_bw() + theme(plot.title = element_text(size=10))

  • Note that when \(\alpha = \beta = 1\), the distribution follows a uniform distribution.
  • The posterior pools information from both the prior and the likelihood to derive a probability distribution for the value of \(p\).

b. Calculate and interpret the credible interval for each of the beta prior parameter settings. Note that the R package binom may be of use.

Conducting Bayesian inference for \(p\): credible intervals

\(1-\alpha\) credible interval for \(p\) is \([a,b]\) such that numbers \(a\) and \(b\) satisfy: \[ P(a \leq p \leq b | x)=1-\alpha. \] where we use derived posterior distribution for \(p\) (here: \(Beta(\alpha^{*}, \beta^{*})\) = \(Beta(\alpha + x, (n-x) + \beta)\)) to derive the value of. Note once we know posterior distribution for \(p\), the values \(a,b\) are fixed.

Conducting Bayesian inference for \(p\): interpretation of credible intervals

Note with Bayesian inference:

  • \(p\), the true success probability, is a random variable (whereas for frequentist confidence intervals, \(p\) is a fixed unknown parameter).
  • Bounds of the credible intervals, \(a\) and \(b\), are fixed numbers (whereas for frequentist confidence intervals, bounds of the confidence intervals are random variables).

Interpretation:

  • (Example for prior \(Beta(0.5,0.5)\)): The probability that \(p\) is between 0.68 and 0.97 is 95%.

Two methods for picking \(a\) and \(b\):

  1. the equal-tailed,
  2. the highest posterior density (HPD) interval.

See a nice plot comparing the two here. Further reference: textbook, 14.3 Bayesian intervals (p.430).

Solution to problem: using binom.bayes to compute credible intervals
?binom.bayes
binom.bayes(x, n,
            conf.level = 0.95,
            type = c("highest", "central"),
            prior.shape1 = 0.5,
            prior.shape2 = 0.5,
            tol = .Machine$double.eps^0.5,
            maxit = 1000, ...)
            
The default type of interval constructed is "highest" which computes the highest probability density (hpd) interval which assures the shortest interval possible. The hpd intervals will achieve a probability that is within tol of the specified conf.level. Setting type to "central" constructs intervals that have equal tail probabilities.

For each of the credible intervals below, the probability that \(p\) is within the interval is 95%.

library(binom)

# 95% credible interval for a Beta(2,2) prior
binom.bayes(x, n, prior.shape1 = 2, prior.shape2 = 2)
##   method  x  n shape1 shape2      mean     lower     upper  sig
## 1  bayes 17 20     19      5 0.7916667 0.6314496 0.9378542 0.05
## as above, but pulling the credible intervals only
binom.bayes(x, n, prior.shape1 = 2, prior.shape2 = 2)[c("lower", "upper")]
##       lower     upper
## 1 0.6314496 0.9378542
# 95% credible interval for a Beta(1,1) prior
binom.bayes(x, n, prior.shape1 = 1, prior.shape2 = 1)[c("lower", "upper")]
##       lower     upper
## 1 0.6599475 0.9591231
# 95% credible interval for a Beta(0.5,0.5) prior
binom.bayes(x, n, prior.shape1 = 0.5, prior.shape2 = 0.5)[c("lower", "upper")]
##       lower     upper
## 1 0.6773164 0.9698094

HW5 Problem 3

a. Preform and interpret the relevant test. Give the appropriate null and alternative hypotheses. Intepret your results, state your assumptions and give a P-value.}

Let \(D_i\) denote the difference in FEV between Year 2 and Year 0 for individual \(i\), and assume that \(D_i \stackrel{iid}{\sim} N(\mu_D, \sigma^2)\). Then, we want to test,

\[\begin{align*} H_0 &: \mu_D = 0 \\ H_A &: \mu_D \neq 0 \end{align*}\]

Since \(n\) is small, we can use the t-test to test our hypothesis.

fev0 <- c(3.22, 4.06, 3.85, 3.50, 2.80,
          3.25, 4.20, 3.05, 2.86, 3.50)
fev2 <- c(2.95, 3.75, 4.00, 3.42, 2.77,
          3.20, 3.90, 2.76, 2.75, 3.32)
diff <- fev2 - fev0
t.test(diff)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  diff
## t = -3.0891, df = 9, p-value = 0.01295
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.25465006 -0.03934994
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##    -0.147

For \(\alpha = 0.05\), we reject the null and conclude that there may be a change in FEV between Year 2 and Year 0 for individuals in this population. The 95% confidence interval is given by \((-0.25, -0.04)\) which does not contain 0, further verifying that the difference in FEV between the two years is not zero.

b. A large test comparing the two-year decline in non-smokers of a different age. Perform a sample size calculation to detect a change in FEV over two years at least as large as that detected for males age 35-39. Use the data above a for any relevant constants that you might need.

  • Suppose we want a two-sided test for the change in FEV.
  • And 80% power and \(\alpha = 0.05\) (must specify desired power and \(\alpha\) level).
  • Estimate the mean and standard deviation of the 2-year FEV difference from the current study and use power.t.test for sample size claculation.
power.t.test(delta = mean(diff), sd = sd(diff), 
             power = 0.8, sig.level = 0.05, 
             alternative = "two.sided", type = "one.sample")
## 
##      One-sample t test power calculation 
## 
##               n = 10.30858
##           delta = 0.147
##              sd = 0.1504844
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.8
##     alternative = two.sided

Since \(n\) is integer valued, we find we need a sample size of 11 individuals to achieve the desired power for an \(\alpha = 0.05\) test.

Book Chapter 18 Problem 10 (p.554)

a. Empirical power

set.seed(34534)
nsim = 1000
samp_null = matrix(rnorm(10*nsim), nrow=nsim)
error_alt = matrix(rnorm(10*nsim), nrow=nsim)

mu = seq(0,1,by=0.01)
pwr = vector(length=length(mu))
for (i in 1:length(mu)){
    pwr[i] = mean(sapply(1:nsim, function(x) t.test(samp_null[x,], mu[i]+error_alt[x,], var.equal=TRUE)$p.value<0.05))
}
plot(mu, pwr, xlab="mu", ylab="Power", main="Empirical power", type="l")

b. Theoretical power

pwr.theo = power.t.test(10,delta=mu, type="two.sample")$power
plot(pwr.theo, pwr, xlab="Theoretical power", ylab = "Empirical power", main="")
abline(a=0, b=1, col="red")
